{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510876"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:34:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11656"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11656"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.01,0.07,0.83,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72564"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"646"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department with severe left-sided chest pain after falling three metres off a ladder onto concrete. He is unable to speak in full sentences due to difficulty breathing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears severely distressed. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 86% on 10 L/min oxygen via face mask, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are reduced breath sounds on the left, uneven chest wall movement, and tracheal deviation to the right. There are bilateral basal crepitations and mild pedal oedema. A portable chest X-ray is performed in the trauma bay as part of the primary survey (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV furosemide and CPAP","4 L/min nasal oxygen","Endotracheal intubation","Needle decompression","Thoracotomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a left-sided tension pneumothorax following trauma, evidenced by respiratory distress, tracheal deviation to the right, reduced breath sounds, and haemodynamic compromise. While there are some signs that could suggest heart failure (crepitations, pedal oedema), the acute presentation following trauma and asymmetric findings make tension pneumothorax the more immediate concern. Tension pneumothorax can be rapidly fatal as increasing intra-thoracic pressure decreases venous return, leading to obstructive shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is urgently required as the patient shows signs of haemodynamic compromise. This is performed by inserting a large-bore intravenous cannula into either the second intercostal space in the midclavicular line or the fifth intercostal space in the mid-axillary line. After decompression, a formal intercostal catheter should be placed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4 L/min nasal oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for this critically ill patient. While some clinicians believe high-flow oxygen may increase the rate of pneumothorax reabsorption, there is poor evidence to support this practice, and it would not address the immediate life-threatening situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV furosemide and CPAP\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for acute pulmonary oedema, but would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous in this case as it may worsen the pneumothorax by increasing intra-thoracic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E alone will not resolve the tension pneumothorax and may worsen the situation by increasing intrathoracic pressure during positive pressure ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThoracotomy\u003C/strong\u003E may be required if needle decompression fails, but it is not the first-line management and requires appropriate surgical expertise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tension pneumothorax requires immediate needle decompression to prevent obstructive shock and cardiorespiratory arrest","Clinical signs of tension pneumothorax include tracheal deviation away from affected side, reduced breath sounds, and haemodynamic compromise","High-flow oxygen therapy does not accelerate pneumothorax reabsorption"],"references":["Pneumothorax. In: Therapeutic guidelines [online]. Available at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ap1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Respiratory\u0026topicfile=pneumothorax\u0026guidelinename=Respiratory\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e208#toc_d1e188","Paydar S, Farhadi P, Ghaffarpasand F. Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) Tips to Be Kept In Mind. Bull Emerg Trauma. 2013 Jan;1(1):49-51. PMID: 27162823; PMCID: PMC4771244. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4771244/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72564"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11656"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15940"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15940"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8a76bee8-430f-48a0-a231-4597847dbcbd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8a76bee8-430f-48a0-a231-4597847dbcbd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":574,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72564"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-03T08:31:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-03T08:31:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88369"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms"